                type="document" xml:id="d698">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On November 11, Admiral Joy issued a statement to the press the text of which is
                    printed in the Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, December 24,
                    1951, page 1035. In support of the United Nations Command position, Admiral Joy
                    asserted that the goals of the delegation were to establish a demilitarized zone
                    reflecting the military situation on the day the armistice was signed; to
                    provide adequate security for the United Nations forces, front and rear, during
                    the suspension of hostilities; to insure against a military buildup beyond the
                    level existing at the time of the armistice; and to arrive at quick and
                    satisfactory arrangements on prisoners of war. The enemy, he said, wanted a <pb
                        facs="1136" n="1120" xml:id="pg_1120"/> finalized zone determined
                    immediately primarily in order to secure relief from United Nations Command
                    military pressure during a <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> cease-fire, meanwhile
                    prolonging the negotiations without cost to himself.</p>
            </div>
